Date:    09 Feb 92 10:58:24 -0500
From:    Arthur Buslik <74676.2537@CompuServe.COM>
Subject: F-PROT says IMV.COM is a virus (PC)

To:  >INTERNET:VIRUS-L@IBM1.CC.LEHIGH.EDU

In the Virus-L digest, vol. 4, Issue 180, of 3 Oct 1991, Bontchev gives an
xx-encoded TSR, IMV.COM, which prevents execution or copying of a file
which has been infected by the DIR II virus.  F-PROT ver 2.02 gives the
following message when this file is scanned using the heuristic scanning
option:

"This program contains several features which are normally only found in
virus programs.  It is almost certainly virus infected."

I disassembled IMV.COM and it is most certainly not virus-infected.  What
triggers the alarm?  The way it opens a file for read access, when the
calling program expects the file will be executed?  Or the way it checks
whether it is already installed in memory by calling INT 21 with AX=A5C1
and checking if AX=C1A5 is returned? Or what?

Art Buslik

