Date:    Sun, 09 Feb 92 11:01:41 -0700
From:    martin@cs.ualberta.ca (Tim Martin; FSO; Soil Sciences)
Subject: Re: Michaelangelo ID sigs comp/w Stoned (PC)

PIPHER@vm.utcs.utoronto.ca (William) writes:

>My question to the net is -- what is an analogous ID string for the
>Michaelangelo virus that I could look for at the same time as I look
>for "stone"?

In fact the two viruses have several good search strings in common,
since Michelangelo is derived from stoned.  But I strongly discourage
the kind of protection you are relying on: it gives a false sense of
security.  The data-diddling variant of Empire, for instance, could be
happily installed on your computer without you noticing. It would be
undetected, except when it came time to restore your system from backup
diskettes: then you would discover that your backups aren't right.
If I give you a search string for it too, then what about Joshi?  Or
Bloody!?  Or the Form virus?  All of these have appeared here at U of
Alberta, so they are probably common at Toronto as well.

I know it is gratifying to use a program one has written oneself, but
in this case I don't think it is the wisest choice.  Others have worked
on this problem full time for a long time, and their tools are much
more effective.

My strong recommendation is:
1. Use Padgett Peterson's FIXUTILS to install a "safembr".  Then you are
protected from (virtually?) all MBR infectors, not just stoned and mich.
It will not use any more memory, will not require anything in your
autoexec.bat or config.sys.  It simply turns the MBR into what Microsoft
should have made it be in the first place.

2. Use the VIRSTOP driver from FPROT, or some similar product, in your
config.sys or autoexec.bat file.  Such products provide much better
protection against all known (and some unknown) viruses.

There are other products as well: the thing I like about the above two
is that they work very well, and the prices are right.

Tim.

