Date:    Sat, 08 Feb 92 06:14:45 -0600
From:    terry@lawton.lonestar.org
Subject: Info on Atari ST and Mac viruses (Mac) (Atari ST)

I have two virus reports to file and one question to ask.  The first
virus was d etected, January 1992, on an Atari 1040STe 4 meg system
using ST Virus Killer Ve rsion 3.84, April 1991 by George Woodside.
The source of the virus was a local  Atari Microcomputer user group
member in Lawton, Oklahoma.  The member acquired  the infection in
Oklahoma City in November 1991.

The virus was identified by the program as "The 'Mouse Inversion' or
'Ghost' Vir us:  This virus does not check boot sectors to determine if
they are already exe cutable.  It hooks itself into the ST operating
system and writes a copy of itse lf onto every disk the ST reads or
writes.  It will overwrite any boot sector, r endering other booting
disks useless.

The virus acts by counting how many copies of itself it has written.
After five copies are made, it starts attacking.  Every five times the
boot sector of eith er floppy disk is accessed, the virus reverses the
vertical orientation of the m ouse.  ST Virus Killer was able to clean
up the effected disk and the virus appa rently has not spread on my
system.  The second virus encountered was in the Mac emulation mode on
the Atari 1040STe.

The virus was detected using Disinfectant 1.1 written in MPW C by
John Norstad .  The virus was detected in 32 files and folders on the
Mac partition of the At ari hard drive.  The source of the infection
was the University of Oklahoma.  I  assume it entered the program
collection on a disk that had been used in the OU  Library computer
center.

The virus detected was a strain of nVIR identified by the program as
nVIR A.  nVIR infects the System file and then spreads to other
applications immediately.   It does not use the 2-3 day delay of scores
and infects each new application run without the 2-3 minute delay.

At first nVIR A only replicates.  When the System file is first
infected, a coun ter is initialized to 1000.  The counter is
decremented by one each time the sys tem is started up and it is
decremented by two each time an infected application is run.

When the counter reaches zero, nVIR A will sometimes say either
"don't panic" (i f MacinTalk is installed in the system folder) or beep
(if MacinTalk is not inst alled in the system folder).  This will
happen on system startup with a probabil ity of 1/16.  It will also
happen, with a probability of 15/128, when an infecte d application is
run.  In addition, when an infected application is run, nVIR A  may say
"don't panic" twice or beep twice with probability of 1/256.

Detection of nVIR A can only be done with a program like Disinfectant
1.1.  There is no way to tell if you have been infected by just looking
at the system.  Disinfectant 1.1 successfully identified and removed
nVIR A (at least that is what  its report said).  I noticed that
certain applications, that had self-reported as corrupted upon
startup, ceased to report the corrupted condition after disinfecting
the system.

I have one other item to report which leaves a question.
Infrequently I encounter a disk that has been damaged while in drive A
on the Atari system.  This last occurred during the download of
scan85.zip, clean85.zip and vshld85.zip.  Floppy disks are only damaged
when the write-protect is off and they remain in the system for more
than several minutes.  Since I operate off of a hard drive the majority
of the time it has not been a dramatic issue.  However, the possibility
of a virus on the hard drive effecting the floppy drive operation is a
possibility.  Could it be that the damage is the result of a virus on
the hard drive of the Atari 1040STe?  Comments on this issue will be
greatly appreciated.

